Observe the constant repetition of the dis· and se· in the compounds in the next six lines. Duff adds that dis· denotes the separation of several, se— of two things. 444. discludere mundum, ‘mark off the world) 446. secernere eaelum. Cf. Genesis i. 6 ‘ Let there be a firma- ment in the midst of the waters . . . called the firmament Heaven'. 447. sorsum . . . sorsus. Lucretius uses sorsum, seorsum and sorsus, seorsus quite indifferently. In five lines iv. 491-5 he has scorsum once, seorsus twice, sorsum twice. In ii. 202 deorsum trisyllable‚ ii. 205 deorsum disyllable. See note on sursum, 1. 465. Notice the change in construction from the infinitive to ut con- secutive with the subj.
